<subSubSection pageNumber="700" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="700">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="700">Note:</emphasis>
The specimen 
<specimenReference collectionCode="LINN" specimenCode="896.2">
Herb. Linn. No. 896.2 (
<collectionCode>LINN</collectionCode>
)
</specimenReference>
(which taxonomically is not 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="700">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1759" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Ononis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">Ononis arvensis</taxonomicName>
as
</emphasis>
currently understood), although annotated with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“arvensis”">&quot;arvensis&quot;</normalizedToken>
(as well as 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“spinosa”">&quot;spinosa&quot;</normalizedToken>
) by Linnaeus, has spiny stems and thereby is fundamentally at odds with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="700">nomen specificum legitimum</emphasis>
which states &quot;ramis inermibus&quot;. This specimen could not possibly have been that upon which the validating diagnosis was based and is therefore not original material for 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="700">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1759" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Ononis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">O. arvensis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
There is no other potential original material and, for this reason, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Förther">Foerther</normalizedToken>
designated a 
<typeStatus>
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
